<div class="recipe">
<p>As it turns out, the secret to getting that signature diner-style flavour is just heaps of butter and sugar. We may not recommend these to be your weekly Sunday morning go-to, but for special occasions, these glorius waffles are sure to impress.</p>
<p>Waffles are surprisingly simple if you have never tried to make them before. However, we will share a few tips to get waffles that are extra fluffy. To start, make sure you do not over mix the flour. Doing so will cause gluten development, which will result in a tougher, chewy consistency. Secondly, you want the batter to rest for about 30 minutes after mixing it. This will allow the flour to hydrate and the baking soda to get better incorporated.</p>
<p>If you don't have a waffle iron at home, unfortunately there isn't a good substitute. However, you can pick up a cheap one that will do a fine job. The more expensive ones will get you more even cooking and more uniform colouring, but at the end of the day, a waffle is still a waffle.</p>
